  <title>Linear-inequalities</title>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Inequality Symbols">
      <title>Applying Linear Inequality Symbols to Inequality Statements.</title>
          <activity>
            <p><em>Work in Groups.</em></p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>You will need a sea- saw.</p></li>
            <li><p>One learner to sit on one end of the sea-saw and another on the other end.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find out who is heavier.</p></li>
            <li><p>Find out who is lighter.</p></li>
            <li><p>Repeat the information using the inequality symbols.</p></li>
              <hint>
                  <p>Assuming that John lifted Mary on the sea-saw, this can be written as:</p>
                    <p>John's mass <m>\gt</m> Mary's mass</p>
                      <p>or</p>
                    <p>Mary's mass &lt; John's mass</p>
              </hint>
                <image source="assets/images/sea-saw.png" width="50%">
                  <shortdescription>Image showing Mary and John on the sea-saw.</shortdescription>
                </image>
            <li><p>6. Share your work with other learners in the class.</p></li>
          </ol>
          </activity>

          <activity>
            <p><em>Work in Groups.</em></p>
              <p>Read the story below and answer the questions that follow.</p>
                <p>Harriet visited a nutritionist. She was advised not to take more than two eggs in a day.
                She was also advised to be eating not less than three fruits in a day.</p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>Why is it important to include fruits in our diet?</p></li>
            <li><p>How can we represent the above information using inequality symbols?</p></li>
              <hint>
                <p>The number of eggs in a day should be <em>less than or equal</em> to 2</p>
                  <p>Number of egg is <m>\le</m>2.</p>
                  <p>The number of fruits in day should be <em>greater or equal</em> to 3</p>
                <p>Number of fruits is <m>\ge</m>3</p>
              </hint>
            <li><p>Share your findings with other learners.</p></li>
          </ol>
          </activity>

          <example>
            <p>Use the symbols <em>greater than or less than</em>to compare the following pairs of numbers;</p>
              <li><p>(a) 4 and 9</p> <p>(b) 16 and 11</p></li>

                <p>Solution</p>
              <p>(a) 4 is less than 9 which is written as 4 &lt; 9</p>
            <p>(b) 16 is greater than 11 which is written as 16 &gt; 11</p>
          </example>

          <example>
            <p>In a village each family has atleast seven goats. Using letter <em>g</em>to represent goatsx, written an inequality to represent the statement given.</p>
              <p>Solution.</p>
            <p>g &gt; 7</p>
          </example>

          <exercise>
            <title>Exercise 1.</title>
           <task>
            <statement>
              <p>Write the following sentences using symbols.</p>
              <ol>
                <li><p>Sixteen is greater than twelve.</p></li>
                <li><p>Forty five is less than fifty five.</p></li>
                <li><p>Three hundred and eighty six is greater than two hundred and eighty eight.</p></li>
                <li><p>Two thousand six hundrend is less than two thousand nine hundred.</p></li>
              </ol>
              </statement>
           </task>

           <task>
            <statement>
              <p>Use the symbol &lt; or &gt; to compare the following pairs of numbers.</p>
              <ol>
                <li><p>28 and 22</p></li>
                <li><p>38 and 48</p> </li>
                <li><p>46 and 39</p></li>
                <li><p>106 and 601</p></li>
              </ol>
            </statement>
           </task>

           <task>
              <statement>
                <p>
                There are x oranges in a bbasket.
                The oranges are either 10 or more.
                Write in symbols an inequality for the above statement.
                </p>
              </statement>
           </task>
          
           <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                A hall can accomodate a maximum of 300 people.
                Using letter <em>p</em> to represent the number of people, write an inequality statement.
              </p>
